2mx.title: Open subproblems in aligning a Task-based AGI

2pf.title: Low impact
2pf.clickbait: The open problem of having an AI carry out tasks in ways that cause minimum side effects and change as little of the rest of the universe as possible.

2rf.title: Shutdown utility function
2rf.clickbait: A special case of a low-impact utility function where you just want the AGI to switch itself off harmlessly (and not create subagents to make absolutely sure it stays off, etcetera).

2rg.title: Abortable plans
2rg.clickbait: Plans that can be undone, or switched to having low further impact.  If the AI builds abortable nanomachines, they'll have a quiet self-destruct option that includes any replicated nanomachines.

2v.title: AI alignment
2v.clickbait: The great civilizational problem of creating artificially intelligent computer systems such that running them is a good idea.

2xd.title: Shutdown problem
2xd.clickbait: How to build an AGI that lets you shut it down, despite the obvious fact that this will interfere with whatever the AGI's goals are.
2xd.text: The "shutdown problem" is creating an AGI which will, on the press of a button, suspend itself safely to disk, and ideally safely [2rg abort] any plans in progress.  *Without,* for example, the AGI carrying out the convergent incentive to build a hidden environmental copy of itself to carry out its previous goal, or to assimilate all matter in the universe towards the goal of making *sure* that the AGI stays safely shut down forever, or having an incentive to prevent the button from being pressed, or having an incentive to positively persuade or trick the programmers into pressing the button.  This problem is often decomposed into the [2rf shutdown utility function] (for the open problem of finding a preference system that identifies the [6h intended goal] of 'just switch yourself off safely (and abort any plans in progress) without doing anything else'), plus [1b7 utility indifference] (for the open problem of finding a way to make a button that changes the AGI's goals, such that the AGI wants the button to continue being there, and doesn't actively want the programmers to press the button or not press the button).  See the entry on [1b7] for more information.

7g2.title: You can't get the coffee if you're dead
7g2.clickbait: An AI given the goal of 'get the coffee' can't achieve that goal if it has been turned off; so even an AI whose goal is just to fetch the coffee may try to avert a shutdown button being pressed.

7t9.title: Attainable optimum
7t9.clickbait: The 'attainable optimum' of an agent's preferences is the best that agent can actually do given its finite intelligence and resources (as opposed to the global maximum of those preferences).

7tb.title: The AI must tolerate your safety measures
